<a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Principle 10.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">: United Nations Principles and Guidelines on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems. A/RES67/187. 28 March 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Statistical significance is a way of estimating the likelihood that a difference between two samples indicates a rea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">l difference between populations from which the samples are taken, rather than being due to chance. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">The significance level is set at 0.05, which means that there is only a 5% chance that the difference in results is due to chance.</span></p></body></html>